name: chlorofluoromethane
Reason: The basic unit, methane has a boiling point of -161.5 degrees Celsius. Adding a chlorine atom we could add ~40 degrees Celsius due to the increase in molar mass and van der Waals forces. Similarly, adding a fluorine atom contributes an increase of approximately 20 degrees Celsius due to its electronegativity and polarisation of the molecule, leading to stronger intermolecular forces compared to the hydrogen it replaced. However, these effects are not simply additive, as intramolecular interactions and overall molecular shape also affect the boiling point. Chlorine has a larger effect than fluorine because it is heavier and more polarizable than fluorine, which likely compensates for the smaller size and higher electronegativity of fluorine.
